III-C Resolving the Non-SPSD Challenge in Discrete Optimization
In this subsection, we formalize the non-SPSD property of (P3) and demonstrate that the proposed framework is explicitly designed to capture this property. The non-SPSD property characterizes scenarios in which identical environmental conditions may correspond to significantly different solutions, which is a phenomenon commonly observed in mixed-discrete wireless resource allocation problems.
Property 2 (Non-SPSD Property of (P3)): Given that the system parameter of (P3) consists of blocks, i.e., , proximity of parameter blocks does not guarantee identical membership in . More precisely, for any given tolerance , there exist instances of (P3) (i.e., choices of ) and distinct indices and such that the corresponding blocks are -close, yet their membership status in differs. Formally, non-SPSD property is defined as
Many mixed-discrete wireless resource allocation problems possess this non-SPSD property, including the two examples elaborated in Section II-C. For instance, in (P6), when the UE-AP pair and have identical channel conditions, i.e., , their association solutions can be and , due to the strong interference between them as modeled in the rate function (LABEL:equ9). Similarly, in (P9), when CP and CP have near-identical channel conditions and positions, i.e., and , their positioning solutions can be and , due to the coupled discrete constraints (13).
Crucially, thanks to our proposed attention-based encoder-decoder structure with the dynamic context embedding, the proposed DVLN is capable of capturing the non-SPSD property on the discrete solutions, as stated below.
Proposition 1 (Non-SPSD Property of ): Let . The DVLN is capable of producing the output such that even if .
Proof.
When , the encoder in (20) outputs identical embeddings , since the encoder cannot distinguish between identical inputs without a judicious design [24]. We can see from (24) that their attention scores are also the same, i.e., if both and belong to the candidate set at step . However, since at most only one of them (say ) can be selected to be included in , this makes the context vector at step different from the previous at step . Consequently, the attention score of the remaining will also change in the subsequent decoding steps. This enables the capability of to produce such that while (or vice versa). ∎
